NT6 only has terminal productions ‘t3’, ‘t43’, ‘t47’ and a binary rule. Hence NT6 cannot produce “t79” alone. Therefore the grammar cannot generate “t1 t79.”

so NT1 must derive the first terminal “t41” and NT6 the second “t34.”  

Looking at the unary (terminal) rules:  
• NT0 → ‘t41’  
• NT1 → ‘t34’  

No rule makes NT1 produce ‘t41’ nor NT6 produce ‘t34.’  And there is no binary rule A → NT0 NT1 (which would connect NT0→‘t41’ and NT1→‘t34’ under S). Thus “t41 t34” cannot be derived.

and NT1 and NT6 must each produce exactly one terminal.  

1. NT1 does in fact have the rule

   so NT1 ⇒ t15.  

2. NT6 must produce the second token, t57, in one step.  Its only unary (terminal) rules are  
     NT6 → 't3' | 't43' | 't47'  
   and its binary rule NT6 → NT0 NT4 would produce two terminals (not one).  None of NT6’s productions yields t57.  

Thus NT6 cannot yield t57, so S cannot derive t15 t57.
